I found these snippets:
<details>
<summary>https://psalm.dev/r/41cf16dc2d</summary>

```php
<?php

function foo(): string {
    return bcdiv('1', '1', 2);
}

function bar(): string {
    return bcdiv('1', (string) ((int) (new \DateTime('last day of december this year'))->format('z') + 1), 2);
}
```

```
Psalm output (using commit f5a0622):

ERROR: NullableReturnStatement - 4:12 - The declared return type 'string' for foo is not nullable, but the function returns 'null|numeric-string'

ERROR: InvalidNullableReturnType - 3:17 - The declared return type 'string' for foo is not nullable, but 'null|numeric-string' contains null

ERROR: NullableReturnStatement - 8:12 - The declared return type 'string' for bar is not nullable, but the function returns 'null|numeric-string'

ERROR: InvalidNullableReturnType - 7:17 - The declared return type 'string' for bar is not nullable, but 'null|numeric-string' contains null
```
</details>

@weirdan you should even be able to remove the @template in this case and just use the conditional with the param name:
https://psalm.dev/r/80f91a4817

The issue is still the same, but the @template is not needed here.
